	affiliations = {ADNOC, United Arab Emirates; Ernst& Young, United Arab Emirates},
	abstract = {Objective: This paper introduces an AI-powered framework designed to enhance business and technicaldecision-making, knowledge sharing, and technical advisory. Unlike generic assistants, the systemuses discipline-specific agents with contextual awareness of technical literature, company procedures,best practices, and petrotechnical software. The approach adheres to the C7 framework, which guidesthe development, management, and governance of complex, intelligent systems. By offering scalable,intelligent support tailored to technical domains, the framework empowers Subject Matter Experts (SMEs)and transforms how engineers interact with knowledge and operational data. The resulting systemcontributes to improvements at the process, business, and technical levels. Methods: The proposed agentic framework is based on three pillars: AI-Subject Matter Experts: Agents with discipline-specific knowledge in narrow domains such aswaterflood, thermodynamics, or petrophysics. Field Insights: Agents maintain in-depth contextual knowledge of specific fields, includingtechnical databooks, reservoir performance reviews, field development plans, and historical lessonslearned. This knowledge is continuously updated through a learning loop. Mastery of Petro-technical Software: Agents demonstrate deep understanding of reservoirsimulation, including input-output logic, workflows, and troubleshooting. Equipped with skills such as retrieval-augmented generation, code writing and execution, andsummarization, these agents operate collaboratively in a multi-agent environment to simulate SMEcollaboration and escalate queries from simple retrieval to advanced diagnostics. The architecture is modelagnostic, leveraging Large Language Models(LLMs) and data connectors to internal sources. Results: The agentic system has shown impressive performance across three tiers of value delivery: Efficient Retrieval: Enables rapid access to validate, structured knowledge for engineers and non-specialists. Advisory Support: Provides diagnostic and interpretive assistance, reducing dependence onisolated expertise. Integrated Responses: Delivers scenario-based support by combining technical references, fieldparameters, and procedural logic, enabled by multi-agent coordination. Adhering to the C7 framework (Command, Control, Coordination, Communication, Computing,Correctness, and Compliance), the system aligns with enterprise standards, enabling organized operations,effective teamwork, reliable results, and policy adherence. Evaluation includes ground testing and SMEreview. Pilot deployments in Waterflood, Field A, and Reservoir Simulation have demonstrated up to 60%time savings, faster onboarding, and more consistent decisions. Novel/Additive Information: Implementation uses curated company data and discipline-specific agents,integrating human expertise for continuous improvement. The system is refined through the updatingof documentation, workflows, and prompts, fostering communities of practice, and facilitating expertconsultations. Its architecture enables collaborative reasoning and the integration of technical literature,procedures, and multimodal data, with scalability across disciplines and platforms. This approach deliversprocess innovation by transforming engineering workflows, revolutionizes business decision-makingthrough human-agent collaboration, and advances technical design with agent correctness, advancedreasoning, and multimodal content. It marks the beginning of scalable, extensible reasoning agents that canevolve with future AI capabilities. This work presents a discipline-based, orchestrated, and model-agnostic AI framework, leveragingcurated knowledge, human-in-the-loop, and scalable architecture for technical excellence in subsurfaceengineering." © IPTC 2026.},
	keywords = {Engineers; Human resource management; Input output programs; Intelligent agents; Knowledge management; Knowledge transfer; Multi agent systems; Petroleum reservoir evaluation; Regulatory compliance; Thermodynamics; Best practices; Discipline-based; Knowledge-sharing; Multi-modal; Reservoir-simulation; Subject matter experts; Technical advisory; Technical excellence; Technical literature; Work-flows; Computation theory},
