	abstract = {Automatic text summarization is now essential in enterprise workflows. It supports applications in compliance, healthcare, finance, patents, and social media. This review looks at twenty recent studies across these fields. It highlights specialized datasets like QMSum, Multi-News, Bill-Sum, BIGPATENT, and GovReport. It also discusses advances in architecture, such as hierarchical encoders, retrieval-augmented pipelines, and multimodal transformers. Improvements include query-sensitive and jargon-aware meeting models, hybrid extractive and abstractive approaches for call centers, structure-guided legal and policy summarization, and radiology systems that combine text with image features. Despite these advancements, significant challenges remain. These include factual inconsistencies and inaccuracies, limited adaptability across domains and languages, scalability issues with long documents, over-reliance on ROUGE, and ongoing worries about privacy and compliance in critical areas like healthcare and finance. By bringing together findings, identifying gaps, and tracking adoption, this survey demonstrates how summarization is transitioning from academic prototypes to systems ready for enterprise use. Future directions focus on retrieval-based generation, multi-modal integration, scalability across languages, and reliable evaluation frameworks to ensure effective, useful, and compliant applications in business. © 2025 IEEE.},
