	abstract = {Abstract—To address the limitations of traditional coal mine accident emergency plans, such as insufficient real-time responsiveness, low precision, and limited flexibility, we propose an enhanced coal mine emergency response plan generation system based on Retrieval-Augmented Generation. Initially, QLoRA is applied to efficiently fine-tune the parameters of a large language model, enabling its effective operation in computationally constrained environments such as underground edge devices. Subsequently, a multi-source knowledge base is constructed by aggregating real-time, open-source data from authoritative websites, including accident pre-plans provided by coal mining enterprises and representative national accident cases. This approach ensures the comprehensiveness and timeliness of the knowledge repository. A retrieval-enhanced module, integrating the BM25 and XGBoost algorithms, is designed to precisely recall critical rescue knowledge. Lastly, a professional prompt template comprising five core elements is developed, ensuring that the generated emergency plans strictly adhere to the Coal Mine Safety Regulations and other relevant standards. Experimental results demonstrate that, in tests involving 200 historical accident scenarios, the system achieves an accuracy rate of 89%, a 24% improvement over the baseline model, while reducing the response time to 27 seconds. This intelligent solution offers a robust approach to emergency decision-making in coal mines. © 2026, International Association of Engineers. All right reserved.},
