	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105033664169?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Indian Institute of Technology Madras, Dept. of Applied Mechanics and Biomedical Engineering, Chennai, India; Kansas State University, Dept. of Electrical and Computer Engineering, Manhattan, United States},
	abstract = {Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) and generative AI have advanced rapidly, opening new avenues for domain-specific knowledge discovery, where multimodal information and sensitive data are common. Relying on publicly available cloud based paid enterprise LLMs raises significant data privacy and security concerns, as these models may learn from user data. Furthermore, the responses generated by these LLMs are often unreliable because they lack domain-specific knowledge. As a case study, we present BMATRAG (BioMATerials RAG), a novel privacy-preserving multimodal RAG system that uses Ollama to run vision language models, exclusively on local hardware, guaranteeing data security and privacy for sensitive biomaterial research data. In contrast to traditional RAGs, BMATRAG combines textual and visual data modalities, allowing thorough and contextually aware question answering over scientific literature and books. We introduce BMATQA, the first question-answer benchmark specifically designed for the biomaterials domain, which includes a variety of question types and complexity levels derived from scientific publications related to the application of biomaterials in various biomedical fields. Using BMATQA, we systematically evaluate the retrieval and generation capabilities of different open source multimodal LLMs using the RAGAS framework that offers various evaluation metrics. © 2025 IEEE.},
